    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p>Not published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>122000</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#belzic2022"/>, catalogue <citedRange>B.4</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Προτιμώι">Προτιμὼι</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Νίκαιος">Νικαίω</name></persName></persName>	 
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Protimo fille de Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Protimo daughter of Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Protimò figlia di Nikaios.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
               <p>This woman's name is not attested elsewhere but has the suffix of feminine name very common in Cyrenaica. The corresponding masculine Protimos is known in other regions. 
                   The father's name Nikaios is attested in the fourth century too many times to allow any prosopographical link.</p>
	<p/>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
